{"id":"2302.11586","submitter":"Jos\\'e De Jes\\'us Padua Arg\\\"uelles","authors":"Bianca Dittrich and Jos\\'e Padua-Arg\\\"uelles","title":"Twisted geometries are area-metric geometries","comments":"10 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The quantum geometry arising in Loop Quantum Gravity has been known to\nsemi-classically lead to generalizations of length-geometries. There have been\nseveral attempts to interpret these so called twisted geometries and understand\ntheir role and fate in the continuum limit of the spin foam approach to quantum\ngravity. In this paper we offer a new perspective on this issue by showing that\nthe twisted geometry of a 4-simplex can be understood as arising from an\narea-metric (in contrast to the more particular length-metric). Such\nequivalence allows us to define notions like signature, generalized triangle\ninequalities and parallel transport for twisted geometries (now understood in a\n4-dimensional setting), exemplifying how it provides a new handle to understand\nthem. Furthermore, it offers a new microscopic understanding of spin foam\ngeometries which is notably supported by recent studies of the continuum\neffective dynamics of spin foams.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 22 Feb 2023 19:00:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-27"}
